node.text:
Dropping in the next few days is a 3+ hour video of my basic carbine class we filmed a couple months ago that contains some of the POIs and drills that I run students through. This will be a free video available at @trexarms. No pay wall. No subscription needed. Accessible at any time. If you need to check something before going to the range, or just want to listen to another shooter’s perspective on shooting. And yes… I demo quite a bit.
-
The next one will most likely be pistol or maybe movement/distance with carbine. We didn’t do anything too crazy in this class. It’s just some basics.
-

Vis lasers suck for shooting in MOST cases. There are a few instances where they work well or are necessary: motorcycle helmets, Han Soloing under a table, ballistic shield (sometimes), etc. On a carbine though, your optic is your friend. You can track it more effectively in-recoil, and see a constant sight at all times. Even if you’re off target.

node.text: If you want to get better at anything, you first have to acknowledge you suck. You then need to look for WHERE you suck. I do some weird stuff in static positions and have been working on fixing that. This video clearly shows some of my deficiencies. One of which is how slow I’m getting on the gun arriving into position (mainly because I was focusing on my weight distribution and NOT standing back up). Everyone sucks at shooting. Some people just suck less than others. But there’s always room for improvement.

This was a rather simple exercise conducted by the majority of our customer service team, marketing, and the owners of @trexarms. The next will dive into the problems we experienced during this particular evening and the one following that will focus on the problems from the previous. That’s how you grow as a team.

Training on the range will NEVER be 1:1 realistic. Just like how 64 hour FF courses, live burn training, and fire academies don’t come close to the real thing either. You can introduce certain principles, train on your gear, and get more comfortable in that type of environment: but it’s an unreasonable and unrealistic expectation that flat range training can/should mimic gunfights 1:1. It can’t. Force-on-force can’t either, although it is better. This is why 95% of my flat range firearms training is strictly shooting. The other 5% is something weird like this drill; introducing some “looking” for targets, unconventional gear use, attention to detail, and some medical. But at the end of the day, the shooting in this drill is the same as the shooting in all my other drills… it’s shooting.
-

Running one of the drills @joel.park_ showed me from @practicalshootingtraininggroup. Not sure who’s drill in particular this belongs too. But while it looks super simple: it ain’t. I’m focusing on my grip, not dragging rounds on/off target on the transitions, and focusing on the target itself more than finessing the dot. This is my favorite Glock setup for crushing at the range: Glock 17 with Trijicon SRO. I’m using my Silicone-carbide infused grip (fancy grip tape) Zev did for me years ago. It’s kinda nice.

This is one of the drills I shoot to compare rifle configurations and gear against other setups. 5 rounds at 50 yards within 5 seconds. All A zone required. Focuses on recoil management and marksmanship. Fastest I’ve shot this drill was sub 3 seconds with a 13.9 rifle/muzzle brake/Vortex Razor on 3x. Pretty cool to see how other configurations stack up.

It just depends what you’re trying to do with the rifle in the first place.

node.text:
Strategy > Operations > Tactics.
Everyone and every company should have a thought-out strategy for what they want to achieve. Inside of this purpose, will be operations to enable that outcome. Within each of those operations will be specific tactics used to complete the operation. Here’s a basic example of a strategy with operations and tactical break-downs for @trexarms. (Granted, with no departments or resources assigned to the operation/tactic)
-
STRATEGIC GOAL: Increase personal armament(s) of the average citizen in the USA to enable resiliency and help prevent future regulations on said armaments.
OPERATION 1: Educate the masses about current weapons and technology that the average citizen should possess.
OPERATION 2: Desensitize people to the idea of carrying/owning firearms as a part of everyday life.
TACTICS FOR 1: Publish internet content showcasing a wide variety of different equipment, acquire equipment normally used by the military and show it being used by the average citizen.
TACTICS FOR 1: Find companies with similar objectives who can fulfil customer demand, and sell willingly to citizens and not just government entities. Promote said companies in the process of publishing materials.
TACTICS FOR 2: Publish internet content that does not specifically-target the existing firearms community. Play on cultural trends and demographics already on the edge of firearm ownership.
TACTICS FOR 2: Identify and establish rapport with public figures outside of the firearms community.
TACTICS FOR 2: Utilize social media platforms to demonstrate and explain how normal it can/should be to carry handguns, rifles, and gear about your daily life.
-
These are just a few examples of our strategies, operations, and tactics (I said it). They won't and don't happen overnight. Based on your overall strategy, there may not be a metric to indicate clear victory. But milestones can be created nonetheless as attainable goals.
-
What is your strategy?
-

node.text:
Me and my company will never be blindly loyal to an entire company’s line of products whether we are a distributor or not. Every vendor we work with has products we love (and carry) and products we don’t like as much. And we’re honest with you all and with them about it. That’s how it should be. Companies like Surefire, EOTECH, and Trijicon don’t mind one bit, they respect it even. I tell them on the phone which products we don’t sell of theirs and why, and then we go about our jobs. Some of these companies even ask what could be changed or modified so it meets our standards to then be carried by our company. Consistency wins. That includes saying things that are consistently good or bad.
